Dox and Cur are hydrophilic and hydrophobic drugs, respectively, with inherent fluorescence properties. Therefore, beside GQDs, the fluorescence of these anticancer therapeutic drugs was also determined to investigate their cellular uptake. A study conducted by Kauffman et al on investigation of green and red fluorescence of Dox indicated that due to the wide excitation and emission spectrum of Dox and overlapping of its emission spectrum within 500 and 700 nm, detection of Dox with green fluorescence showed higher sensitivity in treated cells.
                              29
                            Therefore, in this study, the detection of free and encapsulated Dox in the treated cells has been done in the green spectral region. On the other hand, according to the characterization results obtained from fluorescence microscopy, the emission fluorescence spectrum of complexed Cur with MiRGD and GQDs showed a significant blue-shift compared to free Cur at maximum excitation and emission wavelengths of 430 nm and 540 nm, respectively (Figure S2, A). Thus, the detection of encapsulated Cur in the treated cells has been done in the blue spectral region. It should be mentioned that free Cur has two emission bands; one in the green and another in the blue spectrum region (Figure S2, B) therefore, the blue emission of free Cur was detected to compare with the blue emission of complexed Cur in the treated cells. The preliminary results demonstrated that both complexed Dox and Cur with MiRGD and GQDs in nanocomposites 3 (Table. S3) were taken up more efficiently in HUVEC cells than free Dox and Cur, respectively (Figure 4
                           ). Notably, it was found that the uptake of prepared complexes merely based on obtained photographs was lower in HFF cells than αv integrin-over-expressed HUVEC cells (Figure 5
                           ). However, the related results for drug delivery of other complexes should be more investigated. Taking together these results indicated that MiRGD peptide provides an efficient guided drug delivery system for treatment of αv integrin-positive cancerous cells through iRGD domain.
